  • environmental taxes
    • UF : environmentally related taxes
    • BT : taxes
    • RT : environment
    • RT : environmental protection
    • RT : environmental legislation
    • RT : pollution control
    • RT : resources exploitation
    • DEF : Taxes whose tax base is a physical unit (or a proxy of it) that has a proven specific negative impact on the environment. Four subsets of environmental taxes are distinguished: energy taxes, transport taxes, pollution taxes and resources taxes. Taxes should not be confounded neither with payments of rent nor with purchase of an environmental protection service. (OECD glossary of statistical terms)
    • CN : 2012/07 : ENV review for eShare : new concept

  • harmonised templates
    • UF : harmonized templates
    • BT : reporting systems
    • RT : chemicals
    • RT : environmental health
    • RT : environmental protection
    • DEF : Standard data formats for reporting studies done on chemicals to determine their properties or effects on human health and the environment. They are aimed at developers of database systems, as they prescribe the formats by which information can be entered into and maintained in database. By using these templates, governments and industry will easily be able to electronically exchange test study summary information. The templates can be used for reporting summary results for testing on any type of a chemical (e.g., pesticides, biocides, industrial chemicals).
    • CN : 2012/07 : ENV review for eShare : new concept ; checked with Alastair Wood

  • OECD act
    • BT : Council resolution
    • DEF : Legal instruments adopted by the organisation's governing body, the Council. The end products include international norms and standards, best practices and policy guidelines
  • OECD countries
    • HN : The European Commission (EC) "take part in the work of the Organization [OECD]" (Supplementary Protocol no.1 to the convention on the OECD), in other words: a "full participant" in OECD bodies since the establishment of OECD. This is confirmed by Council Resolution in 2004 [C(2004)132/FINAL]. In 1982 the OECD Council has recognized that "a member of the EC could sit on the bureau of a subsidiary body of the OECD and could chair such bodies" [C/M(82)24]. There has been a recent discussion on the participation in the decision making process, in other words: exercising de facto full membership status (beyond the Supplementary Protocol no.1). An internal inquiry in April 2011 has produced a list of bodies in which the EC has full membership status: - Co-operative Action Programme on Local Economic and Employment Development (LEED) [C(2010)39 and CORR 1 and C/M(2010)5] - Development Assistance Committee (DAC) [Resolution of the Special Economic Committee of 13 January 1960 and OECD(60)13] - Special Programme on the Control of Chemicals [C(78)127(final)] - Steel Committee [C(78)171(Final)] - Council Working Party No. 3 on Policies for the Promotion of Better International Payments Equilibrium (WP3) To make matters more complicated the delegation of the European Commission has been renamed "Delegation of the European Union" following the Lisbon Treaty's entry into force on 1 December 2009.

  • value chains
    • RT : business organisation
    • RT : business economics
    • DEF : Full range of activities that firms and workers do to bring a product from its conception to its end use and beyond. This includes activities such as design, production, marketing, distribution and support to the final consumer. The activities that comprise a value chain can be contained within a single firm or divided among different firms. Value chain activities can produce goods or services, and can be contained within a single geographical location or spread over wider areas. (globalvaluechains.org)
    • CN : 2012/05 : STI review for eShare : new concept
